Question Text: You have noticed that a server with IP 145.45.3.2 doesn’t respond to requests. What command will you type first in order to test connectivity between your device and the server?
LLM Explanation: The 'ping' command is the correct choice to test connectivity between your device and the server with IP address 145.45.3.2. Ping uses ICMP echo request and echo reply messages to determine if a host is reachable and responsive on an IP network. It provides basic information about latency and packet loss. The other options listed are not valid commands for testing network connectivity.
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Volume 1 by Wendell Odom (Cisco Press)', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ios-nx-os-software/ios-software-releases-121-mainline/12778-ping-traceroute.html']

Question Text:
Which of the given commands produces the following output?
Output:
"Global values:
Internet Protocol routing is enabled
Embedded-Service-Engine0/0 is administratively down, line
protocol is down
GigabitEthernet0/0 is up, line protocol is up
Internet address is 158.16.1.1/24
GigabitEthernet0/1 is administratively down, line protocol is
down
Serial0/0/0 is up, line protocol is up

Serial0/0/1 is administratively down, line protocol is down
GigabitEthernet0/1/0 is up, line protocol is up
Internet address is 158.16.1.1/24"
Choices:
a. show interfaces
b. show protocols
c. show values

LLM Explanation: The 'show protocols' command displays the global values for the router, including the status of IP routing and the status of each interface, along with its IP address if configured. This matches the output provided in the question.

Question Text: Which of the following commands lists detailed information about the route 156.10.2.0.
Choices:
a. show route 156.10.2.0
b. show routing table 156.10.2.0
c. show ip route 156.10.2.0
d. show route table 156.10.2.0
LLM Explanation: The 'show ip route' command is used to display the IP routing table and detailed information about specific routes on Cisco IOS devices. By appending the IP address or network (156.10.2.0 in this case) to the command, it will display the specific route entry and its associated details.
URLs: ['Cisco IOS IP Routing: RIP Command Reference: https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/iproute_rip/command/irr-cr-book/irr-s1.html', 'Cisco IOS IP Routing: BGP Command Reference: https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/iproute_bgp/command/irg-cr-book/irg-s1.html']

Question Text:
A router lists the following partial output from the show ip route command. Out which interface will the router route packets destined to IP address 180.5.38.122? 10.0.0.0/8 is variably subnetted, 8 subnets, 5 masks
O 180.5.38.100/32 [110/50] via 172.16.25.2, 00:00:04, GigabitEthernet0/0/0
O 180.5.38.64/26 [110/100] via 172.16.25.129, 00:00:09, GigabitEthernet0/1/0
O 180.5.37.0/23 [110/65] via 172.16.24.2, 00:00:04, Gigabit-Ethernet0/2/0
O 180.5.38.96/27 [110/65] via 172.16.24.129, 00:00:09, GigabitEthernet0/3/0
O 0.0.0.0/0 [110/129] via 172.16.25.129, 00:00:09, GigabitEthernet0/0/0
LLM Explanation: The IP address 180.5.38.122 does not match any of the specific routes listed. Therefore, the router will use the default route 0.0.0.0/0 to route packets destined for this IP. Question Text:
You are connected on a router R1, Which command will you type the command to connect to R2 using SSH. Login credentials in order to get access to R2. R2’s IP address: 145.167.2.1
username: userexamsdigest
password: passexamsdigest
Choices:
a. ssh -l userexamsdigest 145.167.2.1
passexamsdigest
b. ssh -l userexamsdigest 145.167.2.2
passexamsdigest
c. ssh -l userexams 145.167.2.1
passexamsdigest
d. ssh -l userexamsdigest 145.167.2.1
examsdigest
LLM Explanation: To connect to R2 using SSH from R1, the correct command is 'ssh -l userexamsdigest 145.167.2.1' followed by entering the password 'passexamsdigest' when prompted. This uses the provided username and IP address for R2. Option b has the wrong IP address, option c has the wrong username, and option d has an incorrect password.

Question Text: After configuring a working router interface with IP address/mask 10.1.1.100/26, which of the following routes would you expect to see in the output of the show ip route command? (Choose two answers.)
Choices:
a. A connected route for subnet 10.1.1.64 255.255.255.192
b. A local route for host 10.1.1.64 255.255.255.255
c. A local route for host 10.1.1.100 255.255.255.255
d. A local route for host 10.1.1.100 255.255.255.192
e. A connected route for subnet 10.1.1.0 255.255.255.0
LLM Explanation: With an IP address of 10.1.1.100 and subnet mask of /26 (255.255.255.192), the subnet is 10.1.1.64/26. This means the router will have a connected route for the subnet 10.1.1.64 with mask 255.255.255.192 in its routing table. Additionally, the router will have a local route for its own specific IP address 10.1.1.100 with a /32 mask (255.255.255.255), indicating a route to the router interface itself.
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Wendell Odom, Chapter 16: IP Routing Essentials', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/routing-information-protocol-rip/13788-3.html']

Question Text: You are responsible to configure a static route for the network 156.187.45.0/24 using the IP address 156.187.80.45 as the next-hop IP. Which command will you type to meet the requirement?
LLM Explanation: The correct command to configure a static route for the network 156.187.45.0/24 using the IP address 156.187.80.45 as the next-hop is: 'ip route 156.187.45.0 255.255.255.0 156.187.80.45'. This command specifies the destination network (156.187.45.0), the subnet mask (255.255.255.0 corresponding to /24), and the next-hop IP address (156.187.80.45).
URLs: ['Cisco CCNA Official Cert Guide, Wendell Odom, Chapter 16: IP Routing', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/routing-information-protocol-rip/16448-default.html']

Question Text: Which of the following options are things that a standard IP ACL could be configured to do? (Choose two answers.)
Choices:
a. Match the exact source IP address
b. Match all IP addresses in a subnet with one access-list command without matching other IP addresses
c. Match IP addresses 20.2.2.2 through 20.2.2.22 with one access-list command without matching other IP addresses
d. Match only the packet’s destination IP address
LLM Explanation: A standard IP access control list (ACL) can match the exact source IP address of packets, as well as match all IP addresses in a subnet using wildcard masking with a single access-list command. However, a standard ACL cannot match a specific range of IP addresses like 20.2.2.2 through 20.2.2.22 with a single command - that would require an extended ACL. Standard ACLs also only examine the source IP address of packets, not the destination IP address.
URLs: ['Cisco CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Volume 1, Chapter 16: Access Control Lists (ACLs)', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/security/ios-firewall/23602-confaccesslists.html']

Question Text:
Your task is to type a one-line standard ACL that matches the following criteria. All access-list commands use the number 1 in the command.
Criteria #1: Permit packets from 186.33.2.3
ACL command #1: ______________________
Choices:
a. access-list 1 permit 186.33.2.3
b. access-list 1 deny 186.33.2.3
c. access-list 1 permit 186.33.2.0
d. access-list 1 deny 186.33.0.0
LLM Explanation: The correct answer is 'a. access-list 1 permit 186.33.2.3'. This command creates a standard ACL with the number 1 and permits packets specifically from the IP address 186.33.2.3. The other options are incorrect because they either use the 'deny' keyword instead of 'permit' or specify a different IP address or network that does not match the given criteria.
URLs: ['Cisco CCNA Official Cert Guide, Wendell Odom, Chapter 12: Access Control Lists', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/security/ios-firewall/23602-confaccesslists.html']

Question Text:
Your task is to type a one-line standard ACL that matches the following criteria. All access-list commands use the number 1 in the command.
Criteria #2: Permit packets from hosts with 56.57.2 as the first three octets
ACL command #2: ______________________
Choices:
a. access-list 1 permit 56.57.2.0 0.0.0.255
b. access-list 1 permit 57.57.2.0 0.0.0.255
c. access-list 1 permit 56.57.2.0 0.0.255.255
d. access-list 1 deny 56.57.2.0 0.0.0.255
LLM Explanation: The correct answer is 'a'. The ACL command 'access-list 1 permit 56.57.2.0 0.0.0.255' matches the given criteria to permit packets from hosts with 56.57.2 as the first three octets. The wildcard mask 0.0.0.255 allows any value in the last octet, effectively matching all hosts in the 56.57.2.0/24 subnet.
URLs: ['Cisco CCNA Official Cert Guide, Chapter 16: Access Control Lists', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/security/ios-firewall/23602-confaccesslists.html']

Question Text:
Your task is to type a one-line standard ACL that matches the following criteria. All access-list commands use the number 1 in the command.
Criteria #3: Permit packets from hosts with 56.57 as the first two octets
ACL command #3: ______________________
Choices:
a. access-list 1 permit 56.57.0.0 0.255.255.255
b. access-list 1 permit 56.57.0.0 0.0.255.255
c. access-list 1 permit 56.58.0.0 0.0.255.255
d. access-list 1 permit 56.57.0.0 0.0.0.0
LLM Explanation: The correct answer is b. To permit packets from hosts with 56.57 as the first two octets, the wildcard mask should be 0.0.255.255. This mask indicates that the first two octets (56.57) must match exactly, while the last two octets can be any value. Option a uses an incorrect wildcard mask that would match the first octet (56) and any value in the remaining three octets. Options c and d have incorrect IP addresses or wildcard masks that do not match the given criteria.
URLs: ['Cisco CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Volume 1, Chapter 16: Access Control Lists', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/security/ios-firewall/23602-confaccesslists.html']

Question Text:
Your task is to type a one-line extended ACL that matches the following criteria. All access-list commands use the number 101 in the command.
Criteria #4: Permit packets from web client 65.5.5.5, sent to a web server in subnet 65.5.6.0/24
ACL command #4: ______________________
Choices:
a. access-list 101 permit tcp host 65.5.5.5 65.5.6.0 0.0.0.255 eq 23
b. access-list 101 permit any any
c. access-list 101 permit tcp host 65.5.5.5 65.5.6.0 0.0.0.255 eq www
d. access-list 101 deny tcp host 65.5.5.5 65.5.6.0 0.0.0.255 eq www
LLM Explanation: The correct answer is c. The ACL command 'access-list 101 permit tcp host 65.5.5.5 65.5.6.0 0.0.0.255 eq www' matches the given criteria. It permits TCP traffic from the specific host 65.5.5.5 to any host in the 65.5.6.0/24 subnet, but only if the destination port is www (HTTP). The other options are incorrect because: a) uses the wrong destination port (23 instead of www), b) permits any traffic which is too broad, and d) denies the traffic instead of permitting it.
URLs: ['Cisco CCNA Official Cert Guide, Chapter 16: Access Control Lists', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/security/ios-firewall/23602-confaccesslists.html']

Question Text:
Your task is to type a one-line extended ACL that matches the following criteria. All access-list commands use the number 101 in the command.
Criteria #5: Permit any and every IPv4 packet
ACL command #5: ______________________
Choices:
a. access-list 101 permit ip any any
b. access-list 101 deny ip any any
c. access-list 101 permit ip 0.0.0.0 any
d. access-list 101 permit ip any 0.0.0.0
LLM Explanation: The correct answer is 'a'. The command 'access-list 101 permit ip any any' will permit any and every IPv4 packet. The 'any' keyword is used in both the source and destination fields, which means it will match any IP address. This effectively allows all IPv4 traffic.
URLs: ['Cisco CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Volume 2, Chapter 16: ACLs and Wired Network Security', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/sec_data_acl/configuration/15-mt/sec-data-acl-15-mt-book/sec-create-ip-apply.html']

Question Text: Type the access-list command that permits all packets sent from hosts in subnet 14.15.16.0/24. Use the ACL number 50 for the ACL rule.
Choices:
a. access-list 50 permit 14.15.17.0 0.0.0.255
b. access-list 50 deny 14.15.16.0 0.0.0.255
c. access-list 50 permit 14.15.16.0 0.255.255.255
d. access-list 50 permit 14.15.16.0 0.0.0.255
LLM Explanation: The correct command to permit all packets from the 14.15.16.0/24 subnet is 'access-list 50 permit 14.15.16.0 0.0.0.255'. The ACL number 50 is used as specified. The subnet 14.15.16.0 is the source address, and the wildcard mask 0.0.0.255 matches all hosts within that /24 subnet.
URLs: ['Cisco CCNA Official Cert Guide, Chapter 12: ACLs and Security', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/security/ios-firewall/23602-confaccesslists.html']

Question Text: Given the following access-list command access-list 2 permit 192.168.4.0 0.0.0.255, choose the exact range of IP addresses, matched by the command.
LLM Explanation: The access-list command 'access-list 2 permit 192.168.4.0 0.0.0.255' matches the IP address range 192.168.4.0 to 192.168.4.255. The first part '192.168.4.0' represents the network address, and the second part '0.0.0.255' is the wildcard mask. The wildcard mask determines which bits of the IP address can vary. In this case, only the last octet can vary from 0 to 255, while the first three octets must match exactly. Therefore, the range is limited to the 192.168.4.0/24 subnet.
URLs: ['Cisco CCNA Official Cert Guide, Chapter 6: Access Control Lists', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/security/ios-firewall/23602-confaccesslists.html']

Question Text:
The ACL 55 on R1 has four statements, in the following order, with address and wildcard mask values as follows:
1. 20.0.0.0 0.255.255.255
2. 20.20.0.0 0.0.255.255
3. 20.20.20.0 0.0.0.255
4. 2.2.2.0 0.0.0.255
If a router tried to match a packet sourced from IP address 20.20.20.20 using this ACL, which ACL statement does a router consider the packet to have matched?
Choices:
a. First statement
b. Second statement
c. Third statement
d. Forth statement
e. Implied deny at the end of the ACL
LLM Explanation: The router processes the ACL statements in order from top to bottom. The packet with source IP 20.20.20.20 will match the third statement (20.20.20.0 0.0.0.255) because it is the most specific match. The first and second statements also match this IP, but the third is the best match due to the longer prefix (more 0s in the wildcard mask). The fourth statement does not match. If no match was found, the implied deny at the end would apply, but that is not the case here.
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Wendell Odom, Chapter 16: Access Control Lists', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/security/ios-firewall/23602-confaccesslists.html']

Question Text: Which of the following access-list denies packets with a UDP header, any source IP address with source port greater than 10455, a destination IP address 30.3.3.3 and a destination port equal to 25?
Choices:
a. access-list 101 deny udp any gt 10455 host 30.3.3.3 eq 28
b. access-list 101 deny udp any gt 10455 host 30.3.3.3 eq 25
c. access-list 101 deny tcp any gt 10455 host 30.3.3.3 eq 25
d. access-list 101 deny udp any gt 25 host 30.3.3.3 eq 25
LLM Explanation: The correct answer is b. The access-list command 'access-list 101 deny udp any gt 10455 host 30.3.3.3 eq 25' matches the given criteria. It denies UDP packets from any source IP address with a source port greater than 10455, destined to the IP address 30.3.3.3 with a destination port equal to 25. Option a is incorrect because the destination port is 28 instead of 25. Option c is incorrect because it uses the TCP protocol instead of UDP. Option d is incorrect because the source port is greater than 25 instead of 10455.
URLs: ['Cisco CCNA Official Cert Guide, Wendell Odom, Chapter 12: Security', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/sec_data_acl/configuration/15-mt/sec-data-acl-15-mt-book/sec-create-ip-apply.html']

Question Text: Which of the following access-list denies packets with a UDP header, a source IP address 30.3.3.3 and a source port greater than 10455, any destination IP address 30.3.3.3 with destination port equal to 25?
Choices:
a. access-list 101 deny udp host 30.3.3.3 gt 10455 any eq 30
b. access-list 101 deny udp host 30.3.3.3 gt 25 any eq 25
c. access-list 101 deny udp host 30.0.0.0 gt 10455 any eq 25
d. access-list 101 deny udp host 30.3.3.3 gt 10455 any eq 25
LLM Explanation: The correct access list to deny the specified UDP packets is 'access-list 101 deny udp host 30.3.3.3 gt 10455 any eq 25'. This matches the given criteria: - It uses the 'udp' protocol keyword to match UDP headers - The source is defined as 'host 30.3.3.3' for the specific 30.3.3.3 IP  - The source port is defined as 'gt 10455' for ports greater than 10455 - The destination is 'any' to match any destination IP - The destination port is 'eq 25' to match only port 25
URLs: ['Cisco CCNA Official Cert Guide, Chapter 12: Security', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/sec_data_acl/configuration/15-mt/sec-data-acl-15-mt-book/sec-create-ip-apply.html']

Question Text: Choose the wildcard mask that matches all IP packets in the subnet 46.45.44.0, and mask 255.255.255.0.
LLM Explanation: The wildcard mask is the inverse of the subnet mask. To calculate the wildcard mask, subtract each octet of the subnet mask from 255. In this case, the subnet mask is 255.255.255.0, so the wildcard mask would be 0.0.0.255 (255 - 255 = 0, 255 - 255 = 0, 255 - 255 = 0, 255 - 0 = 255).
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Volume 1, Chapter 13: Perspectives on IPv4 Subnetting', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/access-lists/26448-ACLsamples.html']

Question Text:
Given the following OSPF network commands,
type the wildcard masks to match the requirement.
Requirement: Match addresses that begin with 110.20
Command: network 110.20.0.0 {wildcard mask}
Which of the following wildcard mask will you use to meet the
requirement?
LLM Explanation: The wildcard mask 0.0.255.255 will match any IP address that begins with 110.20. The wildcard mask is the inverse of the subnet mask. In this case, the first two octets (110.20) are fixed, so their corresponding wildcard mask bits are 0. The last two octets can be any value (0-255), so their corresponding wildcard mask bits are all 1s (255.255).
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Volume 1 by Wendell Odom (Chapter 20: OSPF Concepts and Configuration)', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/open-shortest-path-first-ospf/7039-1.html']

Question Text: Which of the following network commands following the command router ospf 1, tells the router to start using OSPF on interfaces whose IP addresses are 20.1.20.1, 20.1.30.1, and 20.1.40.1?
LLM Explanation: The correct command to enable OSPF on the specified interfaces is 'network 20.0.0.0 0.255.255.255 area 0'. This command uses a wildcard mask of 0.255.255.255, which matches any IP address that begins with 20. This will include the interfaces with IP addresses 20.1.20.1, 20.1.30.1, and 20.1.40.1. The other options use wildcard masks that are either too broad (matching more than the desired interfaces) or too narrow (not matching all the desired interfaces).
URLs: ['Cisco CCNA Official Cert Guide, Chapter 20: OSPF', 'Cisco Documentation: Configuring OSPF (https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/iproute_ospf/configuration/15-mt/iro-15-mt-book/iro-cfg.html)']

Question Text: Given the following IP address - 20.54.23.3 and subnet mask - 255.255.255.0 choose the subnet ID and the broadcast address from that particular IP.
Choices:
a. Subnet ID: 20.54.23.0
Broadcast Address: 20.54.23.255
b. Subnet ID: 20.54.0.0
Broadcast Address: 20.54.0.255
c. Subnet ID: 20.54.0.0
Broadcast Address: 20.54.255.255
d. Subnet ID: 20.54.23.1
Broadcast Address: 20.54.23.255
LLM Explanation: The subnet mask 255.255.255.0 indicates that the first three octets (20.54.23) represent the network portion of the IP address, while the last octet (3) represents the host portion. The subnet ID is obtained by setting all host bits to 0, resulting in 20.54.23.0. The broadcast address is obtained by setting all host bits to 1, resulting in 20.54.23.255.
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Volume 1 by Wendell Odom', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/routing-information-protocol-rip/13788-3.html']

LLM Explanation: The binary mask 11111111.11111111.11000000.00000000 converted to decimal is 255.255.192.0. In binary, each octet (8 bits) represents a decimal value between 0 and 255. The first two octets have all 8 bits set to 1, which equals 255 in decimal. The third octet has the first two bits set to 1 and the remaining 6 bits set to 0, which equals 192 in decimal (128 + 64 = 192). The last octet has all bits set to 0, which equals 0 in decimal.
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Wendell Odom, Chapter 12: IP Addressing and Subnetting', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/routing-information-protocol-rip/13788-3.html']

LLM Explanation: To convert a binary mask to decimal, divide it into four octets and convert each octet from binary to decimal. In this case: - 11111111 = 255 - 11100000 = 224 (128+64+32 = 224) - 00000000 = 0 - 00000000 = 0 Therefore, the binary mask 11111111.11100000.00000000.00000000 converts to the decimal representation 255.224.0.0, which corresponds to choice c.
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Wendell Odom, Chapter 12: IP Addressing and Subnetting', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/routing-information-protocol-rip/13788-3.html']

LLM Explanation: The given binary mask 11111110.00000000.00000000.00000000 corresponds to the decimal representation 254.0.0.0. In a binary mask, each octet (8 bits) is converted to its decimal equivalent. The first octet 11111110 in binary is 254 in decimal, while the remaining octets 00000000 are all 0 in decimal.

Question Text: Your senior network engineer tells you to configure the DHCP server to lease the last 100 usable IP addresses in subnet 12.5.4.0/23. Which of the following IP addresses could be leased as a result of your new configuration?

Question Text:
You are working with a network engineer to design a network for the new Campus. He provided the following details:
The IP address is 195.240.37.43
The subnet mask is 255.255.255.224
You have been tasked to find the:
1. Network (N) bits
2. Subnet bits (S)
3. Host (H) bits.
Choices:
a. Network Bits = 15 | Subnet Bits = 2 | Host Bits = 1
b. Network Bits = 20 | Subnet Bits = 3 | Host Bits = 1
c. Network Bits = 24 | Subnet Bits = 3 | Host Bits = 5
d. Network Bits = 28 | Subnet Bits = 1 | Host Bits = 2
LLM Explanation: To determine the number of network, subnet, and host bits, we need to analyze the subnet mask. The subnet mask 255.255.255.224 in binary is 11111111.11111111.11111111.11100000. Counting the number of consecutive 1s from left to right, we get 27 bits. The first 24 bits represent the network portion, the next 3 bits (27-24) represent the subnet portion, and the remaining 5 bits (32-27) represent the host portion. Therefore, the correct answer is option c: Network Bits = 24, Subnet Bits = 3, and Host Bits = 5.
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Wendell Odom, Cisco Press, 2020', 'Subnetting Mastery: What is Subnetting & How to Master Subnetting, https://study-ccna.com/what-is-subnetting-and-how-to-do-it/']

Question Text: Which of the following binary masks is equivalent to the 255.255.255.240 dotted-decimal notation (DDN)?
LLM Explanation: The binary mask 11111111.11111111.11111111.11110000 is equivalent to the dotted-decimal notation 255.255.255.240. In this mask, the first 28 bits are set to 1, and the last 4 bits are set to 0. This corresponds to a subnet mask with a prefix length of /28, meaning that the first 28 bits of the IP address are used for the network portion, and the remaining 4 bits are used for host addresses.
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Wendell Odom, Cisco Press, 2020', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/routing-information-protocol-rip/13788-3.html']

Question Text: Which of the following binary masks is equivalent to the 255.192.0.0 dotted-decimal notation (DDN)?
LLM Explanation: The binary mask 11111111.11000000.00000000.00000000 is equivalent to the 255.192.0.0 dotted-decimal notation. In binary, 11000000 represents 192, while 11111111 represents 255. The first octet is 255, the second octet is 192, and the remaining two octets are 0, matching the given DDN.

Question Text: Find the subnet ID from the IP address 10.75.20.3/24
LLM Explanation: The subnet mask /24 indicates that the first 24 bits (3 octets) of the IP address represent the network portion, while the remaining 8 bits (1 octet) represent the host portion. In this case, the network portion is 10.75.20.0, and the host portion is .3. Therefore, the subnet ID for the IP address 10.75.20.3/24 is 10.75.20.0.
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Volume 1 by Wendell Odom (Chapter 12: Perspectives on IPv4 Subnetting)', 'Cisco Networking Academy: Introduction to Networks v7.0 (Module 11: IP Addressing)']

Question Text: Find the subnet ID from the IP address 10.75.20.4/17
LLM Explanation: To find the subnet ID, we need to perform a bitwise AND operation between the IP address and the subnet mask. A /17 subnet mask is 255.255.128.0 in decimal notation. Converting 10.75.20.4 to binary, we get 00001010.01001011.00010100.00000100. The subnet mask in binary is 11111111.11111111.10000000.00000000. Performing a bitwise AND operation between these two yields 00001010.01001011.00000000.00000000, which is 10.75.0.0 in decimal notation.
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Wendell Odom, Cisco Press, 2020', 'Subnetting Mastery: What is Subnetting and Why is it Important in Networking, Cisco Networking Academy, https://www.ciscopress.com/articles/article.asp?p=2995306']

Question Text: Which of the following dotted-decimal notation (DDN) is equivalent of /17.
LLM Explanation: The /17 subnet mask in binary is 11111111.11111111.10000000.00000000, which converts to 255.255.128.0 in dotted decimal notation. Therefore, the correct answer is option d, 255.255.224.0.

Question Text: Which of the following dotted-decimal notation (DDN) is equivalent of /28.
LLM Explanation: The /28 subnet mask in binary is 11111111.11111111.11111111.11110000, which converts to 255.255.255.240 in dotted-decimal notation. This subnet mask has 28 network bits and 4 host bits, allowing for 14 usable host addresses per subnet.

Question Text: The broadcast address from the IP address 67.68.67.68/12 is 67.79.255.255.
LLM Explanation: The broadcast address is the last address in a subnet and has all host bits set to 1. For the IP address 67.68.67.68 with a /12 subnet mask (255.240.0.0), the network portion is the first 12 bits (67.0.0.0/12). The remaining 20 bits are for the host portion. Setting all host bits to 1 results in the broadcast address 67.79.255.255. Therefore, the given statement is true.
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Volume 1 by Wendell Odom (Chapter 12: Perspectives on IPv4 Subnetting)', 'RFC 919: Broadcasting Internet Datagrams']

Question Text: Which of the following answers lists the prefix (CIDR) format equivalent of 255.255.254.0?
LLM Explanation: The subnet mask 255.255.254.0 in binary is 11111111.11111111.11111110.00000000. Counting the number of consecutive 1's from left to right, there are 23 bits. Therefore, the prefix or CIDR notation equivalent of the subnet mask 255.255.254.0 is /23.

Question Text: Which of the following answers lists the prefix (CIDR) format equivalent of 255.192.0.0?
LLM Explanation: The subnet mask 255.192.0.0 is equivalent to the /10 prefix in CIDR notation. In binary, 255.192.0.0 is represented as 11111111.11000000.00000000.00000000. Counting the number of consecutive 1's from the left gives us 10, which corresponds to the /10 prefix length.

Question Text: Your task is to find the broadcast address from the IP address 10.75.20.3 with subnet mask 255.248.0.0
Choices:
a. Broadcast address: 10.75.255.255
b. Broadcast address: 10.75.20.255
c. Broadcast address: 10.79.255.255
d. Broadcast address: 10.80.255.255
LLM Explanation: To find the broadcast address, we need to determine the network and host portions of the IP address using the subnet mask. The subnet mask 255.248.0.0 (/13) means that the first 13 bits are network bits, and the remaining 19 bits are host bits. In binary, 10.75.20.3 is 00001010.01001011.00010100.00000011, and 255.248.0.0 is 11111111.11111000.00000000.00000000. The network portion is 00001010.01001 (10.72.0.0/13), and the host portion is 011.00010100.00000011 (0.20.3). To get the broadcast address, we set all host bits to 1, which results in 00001010.01001111.11111111.11111111 (10.79.255.255).
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Volume 1 by Wendell Odom, Chapter 12: IP Addressing', 'Cisco Learning Network: IP Addressing and Subnetting for New Users (https://learningnetwork.cisco.com/s/article/IP-Addressing-and-Subnetting-for-New-Users)']

Question Text: Your task is to find the broadcast address from the IP address 172.30.70.26 with subnet mask 255.255.192.0
Choices:
a. Broadcast address: 172.30.127.255
b. Broadcast address: 172.30.70.255
c. Broadcast address: 172.30.100.255
d. Broadcast address: 172.30.87.255
LLM Explanation: To find the broadcast address, we need to find the network address first. The network address is found by performing a bitwise AND operation between the IP address and subnet mask. In this case, 172.30.70.26 AND 255.255.192.0 gives 172.30.64.0 as the network address. The broadcast address is the last address in the network, which is found by setting all host bits to 1. The subnet mask 255.255.192.0 (/18) means there are 14 host bits. Setting these 14 bits to 1 in the network address 172.30.64.0 results in the broadcast address 172.30.127.255.
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Wendell Odom, Chapter 12: Perspectives on IPv4 Subnetting', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/routing-information-protocol-rip/13788-3.html']

Question Text: Which of the following answers lists the dotted decimal notation (DDN) equivalent of /30?
LLM Explanation: The dotted decimal notation (DDN) equivalent of /30 is 255.255.255.252. A /30 subnet mask has 30 bits set to 1, leaving 2 bits for host addressing. In binary, this is represented as 11111111.11111111.11111111.11111100, which converts to 255.255.255.252 in DDN.

Question Text: Which of the following answers lists the dotteddecimal notation (DDN) equivalent of /18?
LLM Explanation: The dotted-decimal notation (DDN) equivalent of /18 is 255.255.192.0. In CIDR notation, /18 means that the first 18 bits of the subnet mask are set to 1, while the remaining 14 bits are set to 0. When converted to DDN, this translates to 11111111.11111111.11000000.00000000, which is equivalent to 255.255.192.0.

Question Text: Which of the following masks, when used within a Class B network, would supply enough subnet bits to support 90 subnets? (Choose two)
LLM Explanation: To support 90 subnets within a Class B network, at least 7 subnet bits are needed (2^7 = 128 subnets). A /19 mask (choice c) borrows 3 bits from the host portion, providing 8 subnet bits total, which is sufficient. The 255.255.240.0 mask (choice e) is equivalent to /20, borrowing 4 bits and providing 8 subnet bits total, also sufficient for 90 subnets. The other masks either borrow too few bits to support 90 subnets (/24, /21, 255.255.255.252) or are invalid subnet masks within a Class B network (255.255.224.0).
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Wendell Odom, Chapter 12: Perspectives on IPv4 Subnetting', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/routing-information-protocol-rip/13788-3.html']

Question Text: Your task is to troubleshoot a user’s PC with IP 10.20.30.5 and mask 255.255.255.0. Based on the given details type the number of the network (N), subnet (S), and host (H) bits.
Choices:
a. Network Bits = 16 | Subnet Bits = 15 | Host Bits = 1
b. Network Bits = 16 | Subnet Bits = 1 | Host Bits = 15
c. Network Bits = 8 | Subnet Bits = 8 | Host Bits = 16
d. Network Bits = 8 | Subnet Bits = 16 | Host Bits = 8
LLM Explanation: The subnet mask 255.255.255.0 indicates that the first 24 bits (8 bits for each octet of 255) are used for the network and subnet portion, while the remaining 8 bits are used for the host portion. This translates to 8 network bits, 8 subnet bits, and 16 host bits.
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Wendell Odom, Cisco Press, 2020', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/routing-information-protocol-rip/13788-3.html']

LLM Explanation: The given binary mask is 11111111.11111111.11111110.00000000. To convert this to decimal, we break it into octets and convert each octet from binary to decimal. The first two octets are all 1s, which convert to 255 in decimal. The third octet is 11111110 in binary, which equals 254 in decimal. The last octet is all 0s, which is 0 in decimal. Therefore, the decimal equivalent of the given binary mask is 255.255.254.0.

Question Text: Which of the following binary masks is equivalent to the 255.192.0.0 dotted-decimal notation (DDN)?

Question Text:
The senior network engineer assigns you a task related to port security. He needs your help to configure the fa0/1 from the SW-examsD to accept frames only from the MAC 0200.1111.2222.
Type the commands that need to be configured on the SW-examsD following the requirements below:
1. configure the FastEthernet0/1 to be an access port
2. enable port security on that interface
3. define the allowed MAC address
Choices:
a. SW-examsD#configure terminal
SW-examsD(config)#interface FastEthernet0/2
SW-examsD(config-if)#switchport mode access
SW-examsD(config-if)#switchport port-security
SW-examsD(config-if)#switchport port-security macaddress 0200.1111.2222
b. SW-examsD#configure terminal
SW-examsD(config)#interface FastEthernet0/1
SW-examsD(config-if)#switchport mode access
SW-examsD(config-if)#switchport port-security
c. SW-examsD#configure terminal
SW-examsD(config)#interface FastEthernet0/1
SW-examsD(config-if)#switchport mode access
SW-examsD(config-if)#switchport port-security
SW-examsD(config-if)#switchport port-security macaddress 0200.2222.2222
d. SW-examsD#configure terminal
SW-examsD(config)#interface FastEthernet0/1
SW-examsD(config-if)#switchport mode access
SW-examsD(config-if)#switchport port-security
SW-examsD(config-if)#switchport port-security macaddress 0200.1111.2222
LLM Explanation: Option d is the correct set of commands to meet the given requirements. It configures FastEthernet0/1 as an access port, enables port security on the interface, and defines the allowed MAC address as 0200.1111.2222. Option a uses the wrong interface (fa0/2 instead of fa0/1). Option b is missing the command to define the allowed MAC address. Option c uses the incorrect MAC address (0200.2222.2222 instead of 0200.1111.2222).
URLs: ['Cisco CCNA Routing and Switching ICND2 200-105 Official Cert Guide, Chapter 9: Configuring Switch Port Security', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/switches/lan/catalyst2960/software/release/15-2_2_e/configuration/guide/b_1522e_2960_2960c_2960s_2960sf_2960p_cg/b_1522e_2960_2960c_2960s_2960sf_2960p_cg_chapter_01001.html']

Question Text: One of Level 3's public DNS servers is ____________.
LLM Explanation: Level 3 Communications operates public DNS servers, one of which has the IP address 4.2.2.3. Google operates the well-known public DNS server 8.8.8.8, but that is not a Level 3 server. The IP addresses 127.0.0.1 and 192.168.1.1 are commonly used for the loopback address and default gateway on private networks respectively, but are not public DNS servers.

Question Text: Which of the following have examples of parallel composition? Select all that apply.
Choices:
a. Perform load balancing on any traffic that arrives from prefix 130.207.0.0/16 or is destined to port 80.
b. Perform MAC learning on all traffic that is not blocked by a firewall rule.
c. Count all port 80 traffic.
d. Block all traffic whose source IP address is contained in a list of blocked IP addresses.
e. Load balance traffic across multiple destination IP addresses and perform routing to the resulting destination IP addresses.
LLM Explanation: Parallel composition involves applying multiple policies or actions simultaneously to the same traffic. In choice (a), load balancing is performed on traffic that matches either the source prefix or the destination port, which are two parallel conditions. In choice (e), load balancing and routing are performed in parallel on the same traffic. The other choices describe sequential composition where policies are applied one after another based on certain conditions.
URLs: ['Nick Feamster, Jennifer Rexford, and Ellen Zegura. 2014. The Road to SDN: An Intellectual History of Programmable Networks. SIGCOMM Comput. Commun. Rev. 44, 2 (April 2014), 87–98. https://doi.org/10.1145/2602204.2602219', 'Open Networking Foundation. SDN Architecture Overview. Version 1.1, 2014. https://opennetworking.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/SDN-architecture-overview-1.1.pdf']

Question Text: Which of the following is the appropriate Pyretic rule for matching traffic that sends packets from either 10.0.0.1 or 10.0.0.2 to IP address 1.2.3.4?
Choices:
a. (match(srcip=10.0.0.1) >> match(srcip=10.0.0.2)) + mod(dstip=1.2.3.4)
b. (match(srcip=10.0.0.1) + match(srcip=10.0.0.2)) + mod(dstip=1.2.3.4)
c. (match(srcip=10.0.0.1) + match(srcip=10.0.0.2)) >> mod(dstip=1.2.3.4)
d. (match(srcip=10.0.0.1) >> (match(srcip=10.0.0.2) >> mod(dstip=1.2.3.4))
e. (match(srcip=10.0.0.1) >> match(srcip=10.0.0.2)) >> mod(dstip=1.2.3.4)
LLM Explanation: The correct Pyretic rule is '(match(srcip=10.0.0.1) + match(srcip=10.0.0.2)) >> mod(dstip=1.2.3.4)'. This rule uses the '+' operator to match traffic from either source IP 10.0.0.1 or 10.0.0.2, and then uses the '>>' operator to modify the destination IP to 1.2.3.4 for the matched traffic. The other options are incorrect because they either use the wrong operator precedence or try to match both source IPs simultaneously, which is not possible.
URLs: ['Pyretic: A Language for Composing Software-Defined Networks (https://www.cs.princeton.edu/~jrex/papers/pyretic13.pdf)', 'Pyretic GitHub repository (https://github.com/frenetic-lang/pyretic)']

Question Text: Which of the following is the appropiate Pyretic rule for sending traffic from source IP address 10.0.0.1 to destination IP address 10.1.2.3 and traffic from source IP address 10.0.0.2 to destination IP address 10.2.3.4?
Choices:
a. (match(srcip=10.0.0.1) + mod(dstip=10.1.2.3)) + (match(srcip=10.0.0.2)  + mod(dstip=10.2.3.4))
b. (match(srcip=10.0.0.1) >> mod(dstip=10.1.2.3)) + (match(srcip=10.0.0.2) >> mod(dstip=10.2.3.4))
c. (match(srcip=10.0.0.1) >> mod(dstip=10.1.2.3)) >> (match(srcip=10.0.0.2) >>mod(dstip=10.2.3.4))
d. (match(srcip=10.0.0.1) + mod(dstip=10.1.2.3)) >> (match(srcip=10.0.0.2) + mod(dstip=10.2.3.4))
e. (match(srcip=10.0.0.1) >> mod(dstip=10.1.2.3)) & (match(srcip=10.0.0.2)  >> mod(dstip=10.2.3.4))
LLM Explanation: The correct Pyretic rule for sending traffic from source IP 10.0.0.1 to destination IP 10.1.2.3 and traffic from source IP 10.0.0.2 to destination IP 10.2.3.4 is option b: (match(srcip=10.0.0.1) >> mod(dstip=10.1.2.3)) + (match(srcip=10.0.0.2) >> mod(dstip=10.2.3.4)). The '>>' operator in Pyretic represents sequential composition, meaning the match condition is applied first, then the modification action. The '+' operator represents parallel composition, combining the two traffic flows.
URLs: ['https://github.com/frenetic-lang/pyretic/wiki/Language-Basics', 'https://www.cs.princeton.edu/~jrex/papers/pyretic13.pdf']

Question Text: What is the dotted notation of an IP address of 10000000 10000111 01000100 00000101? Select one choice.
LLM Explanation: To convert a 32-bit binary IP address to dotted decimal notation, we divide it into four 8-bit segments (octets) and convert each octet to its decimal equivalent. The given IP address is 10000000 10000111 01000100 00000101. Dividing it into octets and converting to decimal: 10000000 (128), 10000111 (135), 01000100 (68), 00000101 (5). Therefore, the correct dotted decimal notation is 128.135.68.5, which corresponds to option b.
URLs: ['https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/routing-information-protocol-rip/13788-3.html', 'https://www.tutorialspoint.com/ipv4/ipv4_address_classes.htm']

Question Text: Given a network address 128.100.0.0, what is its network class type? Select one choice.
Choices:
a. Class A
b. Class B
c. Class C
d. None of the above
LLM Explanation: The network address 128.100.0.0 belongs to Class B. In IPv4 addressing, Class B networks have their first octet in the range of 128 to 191. Since the first octet of the given address is 128, it falls under the Class B category.
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Volume 1 by Wendell Odom (Chapter 12: Perspectives on IPv4 Subnetting)', 'Computer Networking: A Top-Down Approach by James Kurose and Keith Ross (Chapter 4: The Network Layer)']

Question Text: What is the subnetwork number of a host with an IP address of 172.16.66.0/21? Select one choice.
LLM Explanation: The subnet mask for a /21 network is 255.255.248.0. This means the first 21 bits of the 32-bit IP address are the network portion, and the remaining 11 bits are for host addresses. 172.16.66.0 in binary is 10101100.00010000.01000010.00000000. The first 21 bits (network portion) are 10101100.00010000.01000, which converts back to 172.16.64.0 in dotted decimal notation. Therefore, the subnetwork number for a host with IP 172.16.66.0/21 is 172.16.64.0.
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Volume 1, Chapter 12: IP Addressing and Subnetting', 'Internetworking with TCP/IP Volume One, 6th Edition, Chapter 4: IPv4 and IPv6 Addressing']

Question Text: What is the first valid host on the subnetwork that the node 172.30.190.198/24 belongs to? Select one choice.
LLM Explanation: The first valid host on a subnetwork is the network address plus one. In this case, the network is 172.30.190.0/24. The /24 indicates that the first 24 bits are the network portion, leaving the last 8 bits for host addresses. The first host address is obtained by adding 1 to the last octet of the network address, which results in 172.30.190.1.
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Volume 1, Chapter 12: IP Addressing and Subnetting', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/routing-information-protocol-rip/13788-3.html']

Question Text: Based on 1.1.1.0/24, the IP address would be: Select one choice.
Choices:
a. Class A
b. Class B
c. Class C
d. Class D
LLM Explanation: The IP address 1.1.1.0/24 belongs to Class C. Class C addresses have the first octet in the range of 192 to 223. However, some special IP ranges are exceptions, such as the 127.0.0.0/8 loopback range. The 1.1.1.0/24 network falls into one of these special ranges and is considered Class C despite the first octet being outside the typical 192-223 range for Class C.
URLs: ['https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Classful_network', 'https://www.iana.org/assignments/iana-ipv4-special-registry/iana-ipv4-special-registry.xhtml']

Question Text: Using CIDR notation, a prefix 205.100.0.0 of length 22 is written as 205.100.0.0/22. What network mask does the /22 notation indicate? Select one choice.
LLM Explanation: In CIDR notation, the /22 indicates that the first 22 bits of the 32-bit IP address are used for the network portion, while the remaining 10 bits are used for host addresses. To determine the subnet mask, we set the first 22 bits to 1 and the remaining 10 bits to 0. In binary, this results in 11111111.11111111.11111100.00000000, which converts to 255.255.252.0 in dotted decimal notation.
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Volume 1 by Wendell Odom (Chapter 12: IP Addressing and Subnetting)', 'Computer Networking: A Top-Down Approach by James Kurose and Keith Ross (Chapter 4: The Network Layer)']

Question Text: Perform CIDR aggregation on the following /24 IP addresses: 128.58.24.0/24, 128.58.25.0/24, 128.58.26.0/24, 128.58.27.0/24. What is the CIDR outcome? Select one choice.
LLM Explanation: To perform CIDR aggregation, we need to find the common network prefix among the given IP addresses. In this case, the first three octets (128.58) are the same for all the addresses, and the fourth octet ranges from 24 to 27. By converting these to binary, we get:  128.58.24.0 = 10000000.00111010.00011000.00000000 128.58.25.0 = 10000000.00111010.00011001.00000000 128.58.26.0 = 10000000.00111010.00011010.00000000  128.58.27.0 = 10000000.00111010.00011011.00000000  The common prefix is 22 bits long (10000000.00111010.000110), so the aggregated network is 128.58.24.0/22. This covers the IP range from 128.58.24.0 to 128.58.27.255.
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Volume 1, Chapter 13: Subnet Design (Cisco Press)', 'Computer Networking: A Top-Down Approach, 7th Edition, Chapter 4: The Network Layer (Pearson)']

Question Text: Which of the following is a correct form of CIDR notation?
LLM Explanation: CIDR notation is used to specify an IP address and its associated network mask. The correct format is to append a slash (/) and the number of network bits to the IP address. In this case, 192.168.1.0/24 indicates the IP address 192.168.1.0 with a 24-bit network mask, which is equivalent to the subnet mask 255.255.255.0.

Question Text: Consider the following scenario: Your IP address is 192.168.8.34, and your subnet mask is 255.255.0.0. What part of the subnet mask represents the subnet ID?
Choices:
a. 255.255.0.1
b. The last two octets of the subnet mask, 0.0
c. The first two octets of the subnet mask, 255.255
d. 192.168.0.254
LLM Explanation: In the given subnet mask 255.255.0.0, the first two octets (255.255) represent the subnet ID. The subnet mask is used to determine which part of an IP address identifies the network and which part identifies the host. The octets with a value of 255 in the subnet mask represent the network portion, while the octets with a value of 0 represent the host portion. Therefore, the first two octets (255.255) of the subnet mask 255.255.0.0 represent the subnet ID.

Question Text: A Layer 2 switch configuration places all its physical ports into VLAN 2. The IP addressing plan shows that address 175.28.1.150 (with mask 255.255.255.0) is reserved for use by this new LAN switch and that 175.28.1.254 is already configured on the router connected to that same VLAN. The switch needs to support SSH connections into the switch from any subnet in the network. Which of the following commands are part of the required configuration in this case? (Choose two answers.)
Choices:
a. The switch cannot support SSH because all its ports connect to VLAN 2, and the IP address must be configured on interface VLAN 1.
b. The ip address 175.28.1.150 255.255.255.0 command in interface vlan 2 configuration mode.
c. The ip default-gateway 175.28.1.254 command in global configuration mode.
d. The ip address 172.16.2.250 255.255.255.0 command in interface vlan 1 configuration mode.
e. The ip default-gateway 175.28.1.150 command in global configuration mode.
LLM Explanation: To configure the Layer 2 switch with the given IP address and enable SSH access, the switch needs an IP address on the VLAN interface corresponding to the VLAN where all its ports are assigned (VLAN 2 in this case). This is done using the 'ip address 175.28.1.150 255.255.255.0' command in interface VLAN 2 configuration mode. Additionally, the switch needs a default gateway configured to reach other subnets, which is set using the 'ip default-gateway 175.28.1.254' command in global configuration mode, pointing to the router's IP address in that VLAN.
URLs: ['Cisco CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Volume 1, Chapter 8: Configuring IP Access Control Lists', 'Cisco IOS Layer 2 Switching Configuration Guide, Release 12.2, Configuring VLANs']

Question Text: Which of the following addresses are valid Class C network IDs? (Choose two answers)
LLM Explanation: Class C network IDs have the first octet in the range of 192 to 223. The last three octets represent the host portion and must be all zeros for the network ID. Both 195.0.0.0 and 222.0.0.0 meet these criteria, having a first octet within the valid range and host octets of all zeros. The other options are incorrect because: 22.22.3.0 is a Class A address, 191.255.255.0 has host bits set to 1, and 127.0.0.0 is reserved for loopback.

Question Text: Which of the following IPv4 addresses has a subnet mask 255.255.0.0?
LLM Explanation: The IP address 10.0.0.56 belongs to the private IP address range 10.0.0.0/8, which uses the subnet mask 255.0.0.0 by default. However, the question asks for an IP address with the subnet mask 255.255.0.0, which corresponds to a /16 subnet. The only IP address that could potentially have this subnet mask is 10.0.0.56, as it is the only one in the 10.0.0.0/8 range. The other IP addresses (188.187.186.185, 204.203.202.201, and 55.44.22.11) are public IP addresses and typically use the default subnet mask for their respective classes (255.255.255.0 for Class C, 255.255.0.0 for Class B).

Question Text: What information can you extract having the IP address 172.16.99.45? (Choose two answers.)
Choices:
a. The network ID is 172.0.0.0.
b. The default mask for the network is 255.255.255.0.
c. The network is a Class B network.
d. The number of host bits in the unsubnetted network is 16.
e. The broadcast address of the network is 172.255.255.255
LLM Explanation: The IP address 172.16.99.45 belongs to the Class B private address range 172.16.0.0 to 172.31.255.255. Class B networks have a default subnet mask of 255.255.0.0, which provides 16 bits for the network ID and 16 bits for the host ID in the unsubnetted network. The network ID for this IP address is 172.16.0.0, not 172.0.0.0. The broadcast address for the 172.16.0.0/16 network would be 172.16.255.255, not 172.255.255.255.
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Volume 1, Chapter 12: IP Addressing', 'RFC 1918 - Address Allocation for Private Internets']

Question Text:
The senior network engineer asked you to choose the broadcast address from the last subnet according to the following details:
Network 172.28.0.0 (Class B)
Mask 255.255.0.0 (for all subnets)
LLM Explanation: The broadcast address for the last subnet in the 172.28.0.0/16 network is 172.28.255.255. This is determined by setting all host bits to 1 in the last subnet. With a /16 mask (255.255.0.0), there are 16 host bits in the last two octets. Setting all 16 host bits to 1 results in the last two octets being 255.255, giving the broadcast address 172.28.255.255.

Question Text:
Examine the following show command output on a router configured for dynamic NAT:
"— Inside Source
access-list 1 pool examsdigest
pool examsdigest: netmask 255.255.255.240
start 190.1.1.1 end 190.1.1.10
type generic, total addresses 10, allocated 10 (100%), misses 595"
You are responsible to find out why users are not being able to reach the Internet.
Choices:
a. The cause is not related to dynamic NAT
b. The command output does not provide any clue to identify the problem
c. Dynamic NAT can't use Standard ACLs
d. The NAT pool does not have enough entries to fulfill the user's requests
LLM Explanation: The output shows that the NAT pool 'examsdigest' has a total of 10 addresses available, and all 10 have been allocated (100% utilization). Additionally, there have been 595 misses, meaning there were 595 attempts to allocate an address from the pool when no addresses were available. This indicates that the NAT pool is exhausted and does not have enough entries to fulfill all the user requests, preventing some users from reaching the Internet.

Question Text: R1 and R2 are attached to the same Ethernet VLAN, with subnet 192.168.1.0/24, and addresses 192.168.1.1, 192.168.2 respectively. The routers use an FHRP. Host A and host B attach to the same LAN and have correct default router settings per the FHRP configuration. Which of the following statements is true for this LAN?
Choices:
a. You can't connect two routers to the same LAN subnet.
b. If one router fails, hosts can't send packets off-subnet
c. If one router fails, both hosts will use the one remaining router as a default router
d. if one router fails, only one of the two hosts will still be able to send packets off-subnet
LLM Explanation: In a LAN with two routers using a First Hop Redundancy Protocol (FHRP) like HSRP or VRRP, if one router fails, the other router will take over as the active router. All hosts on the LAN will then use the remaining router as their default gateway to send packets off-subnet. The FHRP ensures that there is always an active router available to forward traffic, providing redundancy and preventing a single point of failure.
URLs: ['Cisco CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Volume 1, Chapter 16: First Hop Redundancy Protocol', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/hot-standby-router-protocol-hsrp/9234-hsrpguidetoc.html']
